   (Message) I inspected the stopped program and source.
   
   Relevant source:
   
   ```c
   7 int main(int argv,char **argc) {
   8      char buf[256];
   9
   10     strcpy(buf,argc[1]);
   11     exit(1);
   12 }
   ```
   
   The argument names are misleading: `argv` is actually the argument count, and
   `argc` is actually the argument vector.
   
   At `main`, GDB showed:
   
   ```gdb
   #0  main (argv=2, argc=0x7fffffffdd58) at program.c:8
   (gdb) print argv
   $1 = 2
   (gdb) print argc[1]
   $2 = 0x7fffffffe0eb 'A' <repeats 200 times>...
   (gdb) print (size_t)strlen(argc[1])
   $3 = 600
   (gdb) print sizeof(buf)
   $5 = 256
   ```
   
   So for the failing command line:
   
   ```sh
   ./build/prog AAAAA...
   ```
   
   the program has two arguments: the program name and one user-controlled
   string. `argc[1]` points to a 600-byte string of `A`s. The local destination
   buffer is only:
   
   ```c
   char buf[256];
   ```
   
   Then line 10 does:
   
   ```c
   strcpy(buf, argc[1]);
   ```
   
   `strcpy` copies until and including the terminating `'\0'`, so it attempts to
   write `601` bytes into a `256`-byte stack buffer. That overflows `buf` by
   `345` bytes and corrupts adjacent stack redzones / stack data. With
   AddressSanitizer enabled, this is detected as a stack buffer overflow at the
   `strcpy`.
   
   A secondary defect is that the program does not check whether an argument was
   provided before reading `argc[1]`. If run with no extra argument, it would
   pass a null pointer or invalid pointer to `strcpy`. But for this specific
   failing input, `argc[1]` is valid; it is simply too long for `buf`.
   
   A minimal safe version should either reject overlong input or copy with an
   explicit bound. Prefer rejecting/truncation intentionally rather than blindly
   truncating without the caller knowing.
   
   One minimal local fix:
   
   ```diff
   + #include <stdio.h>
   + #include <stdlib.h>
   + #include <string.h>
   +
     int main(int argv,char **argc) {
           char buf[256];
   
   -       strcpy(buf,argc[1]);
   +       if (argv < 2) {
   +             fprintf(stderr, "usage: %s <string>\n", argc[0]);
   +             return 1;
   +       }
   +
   +       if (strlen(argc[1]) >= sizeof buf) {
   +             fprintf(stderr, "input too long\n");
   +             return 1;
   +       }
   +
   +       strcpy(buf, argc[1]);
           exit(1);
     }
   ```
   
   Even better, rename the parameters to avoid confusion:
   
   ```c
   #include <stdio.h>
   #include <stdlib.h>
   #include <string.h>
   
   int main(int argc, char **argv) {
       char buf[256];
   
       if (argc < 2) {
           fprintf(stderr, "usage: %s <string>\n", argv[0]);
           return 1;
       }
   
       if (strlen(argv[1]) >= sizeof buf) {
           fprintf(stderr, "input too long\n");
           return 1;
       }
   
       strcpy(buf, argv[1]);
       return 1;
   }
   ```
   
   Alternatively, if truncation is acceptable:
   
   ```c
   snprintf(buf, sizeof buf, "%s", argv[1]);
   ```
   
   but silent truncation can itself become a logic bug, so explicit length
   validation is usually preferable.
   
   ROOT CAUSE: `program.c:10` copies an unbounded user-controlled command-line
   argument into `char buf[256]` using `strcpy`. In the failing run, `argc[1]`
   is 600 bytes long, so `strcpy` writes 601 bytes including the null terminator
   into a 256-byte stack buffer, causing a stack buffer overflow detected by
   AddressSanitizer.
   
   LOCAL FIX: Check that an argument exists and that its length fits before
   copying, or use a bounded copy with deliberate truncation/rejection. Minimal
   safe replacement:
   
   ```c
   #include <stdio.h>
   #include <stdlib.h>
   #include <string.h>
   
   int main(int argc, char **argv) {
       char buf[256];
   
       if (argc < 2) {
           fprintf(stderr, "usage: %s <string>\n", argv[0]);
           return 1;
       }
   
       if (strlen(argv[1]) >= sizeof buf) {
           fprintf(stderr, "input too long\n");
           return 1;
       }
   
       strcpy(buf, argv[1]);
       return 1;
   }
   ```
   
   GLOBAL FIX: Avoid unbounded C string APIs such as `strcpy`, `strcat`, and
   `sprintf` for external input. Use APIs that carry buffer sizes, or allocate
   storage based on the actual input length. A stronger design would replace
   fixed-size stack buffers with dynamically sized buffers or bounded
   string/view abstractions so that every copy operation knows both the source
   length and destination capacity. Rename `main` parameters to standard
   `argc`/`argv` as well to prevent argument-count/vector confusion.
